data.content:
Your test works but uses generic `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere, which gives poor failure messages. MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions that tell you *what* went wrong:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Clear failure messages instead of just "Expected: True, Actual: False"
    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));    // no built-in "all match" assert, IsTrue is fine here
    Assert.Contains(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Your code | Better alternative | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Says *"collection was empty"* on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Says *"expected 3 but got 5"* on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(admin)` | Says *"value was null"* on failure |

The general rule: **avoid `Assert.IsTrue` when a specialized assertion exists** — you get actionable failure messages instead of just `Expected: True, Actual: False`.
